<subSubSection id="469B363D4BBDA90B0A8372B0A2ED556B" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="E95EBF01F95096ED409C2217235ABD68" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="78E47D4F83AA9EB77EB0EFA277F70774" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<taxonomicName id="6DDC0293B9E3FF39E50B6BD36B403F02" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Niveas</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished from most genera of choreutids by the wing pattern (Figs 1, 3). Superficially, species of 
<taxonomicName id="84CEEFA0485CCD4ED5F0994E6647B105" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Niveas</taxonomicName>
are similar to some species of 
<taxonomicName id="3164107DF63C11654B9D4AEEC291E65C" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Anthophila" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anthophila" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anthophila</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B4683BFD7CE3921AF37F6C28805D59D4" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Choreutis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Choreutis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Choreutis</taxonomicName>
, but there is no known species in either of the latter two genera with a black terminal band enclosing white spots in the forewing as in 
<taxonomicName id="E97194325E4DB8E2C39D70C76667F6C7" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas agassizi" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agassizi">Niveas agassizi</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="214C04B15F6C3DCEFF3A68FED017AD3F" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas kone" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kone">Niveas kone</taxonomicName>
. (Figs 1, 3). Forewing venation with only four radial branches or with R4 and R5 fused in the basal half is also diagnostic for the genus. Female genitalia with paired concave sclerotizations on A7 sternite are also unique to 
<taxonomicName id="9E0F1BAD8B788760DF9F76C6AF2EA8BD" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Niveas</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="85E89AE1E52BEB77562BA19885DCF68A" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" type="description">
<paragraph id="619E5D532AFA3E4C9C8745775E52A89D" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7BC46EE753405C8088159A5004C5C21A" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
Head. Labial palpi with projecting ventral scale tufts (Figs 2, 4). Wings. Forewing veins R four-branched in 
<taxonomicName id="B5A272C9A5579D49D59510A908E47A5F" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas kone" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kone">Niveas kone</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 5), five-branched in 
<taxonomicName id="A6CFB5A994A959A4E1F980AD4BC6A3AA" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas agassizi" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agassizi">Niveas agassizi</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 6), with R4 an R5 fused in basal 3/5; CuP present at termen for 1/3 to 1/5 wing length, extending as fold further towards base. Hindwing ten-veined, with M2 in close proximity to the basally fused M3 and CuA1 (
<taxonomicName id="1C8788CEC2BDF5A9857168811F474252" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas agassizi" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agassizi">Niveas agassizi</taxonomicName>
) or nine-veined, apparently with M3 and CuA1 completely fused into a single vein (Figs 5, 6). Male genitalia. Tegumen rounded on top, tuba analis extending beyond tegumen; vinculum as inverted trapezoid ventrally emarginate; valva with costal margin straight, ventral margin rounded, ending with a horn-like projection; phallus twice as long as valva (Fig. 7). Female genitalia. Apophyses anteriores slightly longer than posteriores; ostium bursae on A7 with a more or less strongly sclerotized antrum; ductus bursae straight, not coiled, with strong lateral sclerotizations; corpus bursae as a single sac (
<taxonomicName id="4DA9C2F5CD2618E905A6B6FA3BDBA18D" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas agassizi" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agassizi">Niveas agassizi</taxonomicName>
) or divided into two sacs (
<taxonomicName id="58738414CC7702E85430DF9811D972D6" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas kone" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kone">Niveas kone</taxonomicName>
) with one or more signa. A7 sternite with paired, somewhat rounded, concave sclerotizations proximally, clearly visible in 
<taxonomicName id="DEED98DBA92228A10E3C34E33B30C4DF" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas kone" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kone">Niveas kone</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 8), and slightly less so in 
<taxonomicName id="D7081B1FAB508827F264C613129DDF16" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas agassizi" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agassizi">Niveas agassizi</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 9).
</paragraph>
<caption id="E3772C07EAA55F59C1BF3D0FB54A4EC5" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<paragraph id="CA33E519830232A4C12179C0F3E6B2C0" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
Figures 5-9. 
<taxonomicName id="DDB7DD18B33450DE4F97E7B8F83212A6" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas kone" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kone">Niveas kone</taxonomicName>
: 5 Wing venation 7 Male genitalia 8 Female genitalia. 
<taxonomicName id="6DF4DDB04A9B4134470ACB2DA400CEC0" authority="Rota, 2013" authorityName="Rota" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Choreutidae" genus="Niveas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Niveas agassizi" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agassizi">Niveas agassizi</taxonomicName>
: 6 Wing venation 9 Female genitalia. (In Figs 8 and 9 arrows point at the A7 sternite sclerotizations, and triangles point at the lateral sclerotizations on the ductus bursae.)
</paragraph>
</caption>
